      },
      "lineNbr": 61,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-03-19T21:04:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e So is ExceptionInfo just code[0]? Changed it up, but not sure what\u0027s correct.\n\nIt could be more. See snapshot/linux/exception_snapshot_linux.cc ExceptionSnapshotLinux::ReadSiginfo. That’s how codes_ is supposed to be used with a signal handler.",
      "parentUuid": "914d08fe_ca1a2223",
      "revId": "cf2c0b2eb9ec889ba0187a92e30b70db5da22388",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e8778b55_2518c036",
        "filename": "snapshot/ios/exception_snapshot_ios.h",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 63,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-03-16T20:23:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "We should probably be using native types for these, although they’ll need a conversion on the way out in order to adhere to the ExceptionSnapshot interface, so it’s not such a huge deal.\n\nHowever, at whatever the point of conversion is, we should be checking to make sure statically that either the source and destination types are compatible (no data loss possible, even in theory), or if not to make sure that the source value fits into the target type at runtime (no data loss in practice).",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 62,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 63,
        "endChar": 30
      },
      "revId": "cf2c0b2eb9ec889ba0187a92e30b70db5da22388",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "413eaa6f_7fb0c23e",
        "filename": "snapshot/ios/exception_snapshot_ios.h",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 63,
      "author": {
        "id": 1116294
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-03-19T20:05:55Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "uint64_t        thread_id;      /* system-wide unique 64-bit thread id */\nand\nvoid    *si_addr;               /* faulting instruction */\nwhich I think is a user64_addr_t, which is a __uint64_t, right?\n\nisn\u0027t this correct?",
      "parentUuid": "e8778b55_2518c036",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 62,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 63,
        "endChar": 30
      },
      "revId": "cf2c0b2eb9ec889ba0187a92e30b70db5da22388",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "01ffcff7_6692fed0",
        "filename": "snapshot/ios/exception_snapshot_ios.h",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 63,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-03-19T21:04:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e uint64_t        thread_id;      /* system-wide unique 64-bit thread id */\n\nThat’s fine.\n\n\u003e void    *si_addr;               /* faulting instruction */\n\u003e which I think is a user64_addr_t, which is a __uint64_t, right?\n\nNo, that’s a pointer, which you can express as a void* (since you’re in-process), or if you want a non-pointer integer, use uintptr_t (integer the size of a pointer).",
      "parentUuid": "413eaa6f_7fb0c23e",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 62,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 63,
        "endChar": 30
      },
      "revId": "cf2c0b2eb9ec889ba0187a92e30b70db5da22388",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
